HW3 Peer Assessment

Background

The fishing industry uses numerous measurements to describe a specific fish. Our goal is to predict the weight of a fish based on a number of these measurements and determine if any of these measurements are insignificant in determining the weigh of a product. See below for the description of these measurments.

Data Description

The data consists of the following variables:

  1. Weight: weight of fish in g (numerical)
  2. Species: species name of fish (categorical)
  3. Body.Height: height of body of fish in cm (numerical)
  4. Total.Length: length of fish from mouth to tail in cm (numerical)
  5. Diagonal.Length: length of diagonal of main body of fish in cm (numerical)
  6. Height: height of head of fish in cm (numerical)
  7. Width: width of head of fish in cm (numerical)

Read the data

# Import library you may need
library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
# Read the data set
fishfull = read.csv("C:\\Users\\adri_\\Documents\\Gatech\\ISYE6414\\Homeworks\\3-Multiple_linear_regression_part 2\\Fish.csv",header=T, fileEncoding = 'UTF-8-BOM')
row.cnt = nrow(fishfull)
# Split the data into training and testing sets
fishtest = fishfull[(row.cnt-9):row.cnt,]
fish = fishfull[1:(row.cnt-10),]

Please use fish as your data set for the following questions unless otherwise stated.

Question 1: Exploratory Data Analysis [10 points]

(a) Create a box plot comparing the response variable, Weight, across the multiple species. Based on this box plot, does there appear to be a relationship between the predictor and the response?

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(fish, aes(

  stat_summary(fun.y=mean, geom="point", shape=20, size=4, color="red", fill="red") + 
  theme(legend.position = "none") + ggtitle("Weight with respect to species") + 
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Answer Yes,there is a relationship between the weight and the species. The mean weight in Pike fishes is larger than the rest of the species. In contrast, Smelt, Roach and Parkki fishes have smaller mean weight than the rest of the species.

(b) Create plots of the response, Weight, against each quantitative predictor, namely Body.Height, Total.Length, Diagonal.Length, Height, and Width. Describe the general trend of each plot. Are there any potential outliers?

#Weight is the response variable

     xlab="Body height",
     ylab="Weight",

     col = "red",
     pch=20)

     xlab="Total length",
     ylab="Weight",

     xlab="Diagonal length",
     ylab="Weight",

     col = "purple",
     pch=20)

     xlab="Height",
     ylab="Weight",
     main="Weight by Height",
     col = "orange",

     xlab="Width",
     ylab="Weight",
     main="Weight by Width",
     col = "blue",
     pch=20)

Answer Weight by Body height: In this plot, it appears to be two (2) different clusters of data. One with a positive trend and a maximum value for weight of $1,000 g, and the other with weight increasing by body weight with maximum values of weight around 1,600 or 1,700 g.Overall, there is an indication that the weight increases linearly with respect to the body weight. In addition, there seems to be a potential outlier in the data. Weight by Total length: In this plot, it appears to be two (2) different clusters of data. One with a positive trend and a maximum value for weight of $1,000 g, and the other with weight increasing by total length with maximum values of weight around 1,600 or 1,700 g.Overall, there is an indication that the weight increases linearly with respect to the total length. In addition, there seems to be the potential of an outlier in the data. Weight by Diagonal length: In this plot, it appears to be two (2) different clusters of data. One with a positive trend and a maximum value for weight of $1,000 g, and the other with weight increasing by diagonal length with maximum values of weight around 1,600 or 1,700 g.Overall, there is an indication that the weight increases linearly with respect to the diagonal length. In addition, there seems to be an outlier in the data. Weight by Height: In this plot, it appears to be two (3) different clusters of data. Two of these clusters, exhibit trends with maximum values for weight of $1,000 g but one slope is steeper than the other, and the third trend is also posititve with weight increasing by height with maximum values of weight around 1,600 - 1,700 g and somewhat scatter at the end of the slope.Overall, there is an indication that the weight increases linearly with respect to the height. Although it is not clear how many of the observations are outliers in this plot, at least one of them is potentially an outlier around the weight 1500-1700 g. Weight by Width: The data presents itself very nicely in this plot, with positive trends and the weight increasing linearly with width.There are some potential outliers on weight 1500-1700 g.
